<font color="#FF0000">CONTINUING TO LEARN</font><br>
<tt>Sun Feb 16 14:56:54 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
To docdel, and others I may have offended or irked.  My apology is offered. Being a shrink for so long, I guess I just assumed that everyone was &quot;psych&quot; minded and in touch with their emotions as I was.... as I thought I was that is....  Return to this site, and these posts, has taught me that I had become closed off in smug answers and opinions, convictions I didn't need to rethink.<br><br>
When I first came &quot;under attack&quot; I became defensive and confused. Afterall, I had the moral high ground. Who were these anonomous veterans to question me? (I'm the doc, right?)  I pulled back and regrouped, and a strange think happened. My smug opinions and positions, most of which had gone unchallenged for years, just didn't work anymore.  I guess the old line that &quot;you can lead a shrink to water, but you can't make him think&quot; applied here.  I am grateful to all of you for helping me &quot;break on through&quot; and to better understanding of all of us and all of our experiences.<br><br>
Viet Nam made me a shrink, as strange as that sounds.  There were 3 of us in High School. Tom, low grades but a hot 55 chevy, a true car nut. Ron, the joiner, had a Corvette, went to college and joined a fraternity. Barry, too smart for his own good, with a fast car and a faster girl friend, went to college and majored in war protesting.  Tom came home in a bag. Ron, always the joiner, joined the Navy, and last I heard was a Captain and upward bound.  I went from protests to drugs to hippidome to eventually counseling others as a draft counslor and then for bad trips at the local Free Clinic as a drug counselor. The counseling ability came naturally, and graduate school in psych followed.  I was lucky, alot luckier than the long list of dead classmates hanging on the wall at my 25 high school reunion. There but for the grace...   <br><br>
Somewhere in the last 25 years of being a therapist, with cops, with vets (alot), PTSD victims (alot) and regular neurotics, psychos, etc., I stopped thinking about Viet Nam and its impact on me.  This site has torn off my blinders.  <br><br>
When I was 18, on my birthday, I went to the Selective Service Board and registered. I was really proud.  I went home and showed my dad my draft card.  The look in his eyes was strange, and his mood quiet.  I didn't know why then.  Now I have a son about to turn 18, and there is no draft board, and no draft cards, and no friends coming home in bags, and now, finally, I understand the look in my dad's eyes that day long ago.<br><br>
doc     (Special thanks to Brian)
